segments.text: Let's turn to your retirement then.
I was wondering, you retired from the military because of your thirty years.
Thirty years service, that's right.
And so there was no chance of staying on then?
The only chance of staying on was getting in a promotion spot, being the division commander, and General Rutter and I are the same age and he was in it.
had no reason to retire.
And the only way he had to get another star, then.
He had a second star.
Yeah, but I mean, for you.
And the only way for me to get a second star would be get into his job, or similar jobs somewhere in the United States.
And of course, they keep that within an Army area.
Yeah.
So there was no place for me.
And I got what they call a statutory requirement.
It's 30 years, period.
Yeah.
I was BG for seven years, permanent rank, and it was pretty good.
Now, how did you feel on the day you retired?
Well, I felt with mixed emotions.
I had to have mixed emotions.
I was leaving something that I had nurtured from something that was mediocre to something that was superior.
And I built it up.
I could see myself accomplishing something.
And I had that tremendous satisfaction in knowing that I had accomplished something.
On the other hand, I've known the regulations for 30 years or more.
And you're facing it.
Yeah.
Nothing you can do about it.
Nothing you can do about it except conform.
It's the law of the land.
It's the Army regulations, so to speak, ARs.
And the only way I could have stayed on was by being promoted.
And there was no spot for it.
Of course, you had a lot to look forward to in the civilian world, too.
You bet.
I had a going business that I carried forward.
I was deeply engrossed with it, very active.
A lot of people said Brunt Company was a one-man show, so to speak.
It wasn't a one-man show, but it was one-man direction.
It was my money, and I was looking after it.
That's another way of putting it.
I was making it appreciated by virtue of working and making it earn me money.
If you have to, well, let's do this.
When we take a look at your, over your 30 years now,

I'd like to know what things in the military over those three decades stand out as what you'd call your achievements and what things stand out as oh maybe shortcomings you just couldn't finish something or get something obviously a general doesn't have very many failures but I mean just something that you couldn't accomplish
In the Army, I don't know of anything that I'd set out to do that I didn't accomplish.
In combat and all my Army work, up until I got in the 9th Divardy, I accomplished what I wanted.
In the little picture, meaning I did a superior job and I traded for it and that's that.
In the 90th Divardy, I set my goals of being combat proficient for the Divardy, meaning all of its parts.
And like I say, it was a five-year program.
I didn't start on it.
and set my sights and my direction until the second year, in the second year.
So it was a five-year program, and I accomplished it on the fifth year.
In total, I accomplished it with two battalions first, and then the three battalions, and then the fourth battalion.
So you'd probably consider that your finest achievement?
I consider that I left out division artillery, combat proficient, period.
And that's all any commander can ask for.
Sure.
I turn it over to my successor.
I turn it over back to General Rutter.
General, your division artillery is combat proficient.
It's passed its test on the critical army eyes, and there's nothing more I can say about it.
That's all I had to say.
That's right.
That's all I had to say.
I enjoyed working for you, and I'll see you next football game maybe.
Something like that.
He and I used to go to a lot of football games together.
Let's talk about General Rutter because it was during his years that there were so many changes at A&M that I want to get your opinion on, but first let's talk about Earl Rutter.
Earl Rutter was a salt of the earth.
No question about it.
He came from, I don't know whether you know where Eden is or not.
No, I don't.
He was born out in Eden, out in Concho County, which you know where San Angelo is.
Well, San Angelo is up in that part of the county and Eden is down in this part of the county.
And it's ranching country, goat ranches, sheep ranches, some cattle.
But he went to school there, grammar school and high school, probably a one-room school, if you knew the truth of it.
It's a very small town.
It's just a big crossroads with a couple of truck stops and a general mercantile store and a drug store and a couple of cafes.
One nice cafe and one coffee shop.
It's terrible.
I built three jobs in that county.
So I've been to all the truck stops there.
I guess there's maybe 300-400 people living, eating proper, and of course the ranchers and all that.
What kind of man was Rudder?
They said he's the salt of the earth.
He's the salt of the earth, that's right.
He's, well, to start with, he's a rancher boy.
And all he knows is hard work and honesty and being a good fellow.
He went up to John Tarleton,
from high school.
And one of the ranchers gave him a milk cow when he went up there.
And he took this damn cow up there and sold milk to get through college.
And of course, John Tarleton then was a junior college.
and he played football up there and got a football scholarship to go to A&M and so he went down there and finished his Union senior year at A&M.
That happened in 1932.
He was down in the infantry and I was in the artillery so I would pass one another, knew one another, but not eminently.
He was a very capable person, business-wise.
After he got out of the Army in 1945 or 6, whenever he got out, I don't know, he went back to Brady, which is a county seat just below Eden in McCulloch County.

bought into or bought a royal tire store, combination appliance store and filling station and you know, sold all kinds of refrigerators and tires and stoves and that type of store and had a couple gasoline pumps out front.
Basically a tire and appliance store.
on his U.S. Royal.
And he participated in civic enterprises and elected mayor over there.
And did a good job as mayor of Brady and was very civic minded and

They had a scandal down in the Texas Land Board, Land Commissioner had this program of veteran benefits and that they would help you buy a farm or a ranch up to 10 acres or $7,500 I think was the maximum at that time anyway.
And they caught one of the then
I want to say Baskin-Giles.
I don't know whether that was that fellow's name or not.
Anyway, they caught him buying up property and then selling it to this program.
And as soon as they did, why, they tried him and convicted him.
And of course, that relieved him of his land commissioner's job.
And the governor appointed the mayor of Brady, which is Earl Rudder, land commissioner.
And Earl went down there and straightened it out and established certain protective steps to going through this process that eliminated that possibility anymore.
He set it up at the county judge in your particular area, and maybe the county auditor and somebody else set it on a land board.
to where they had to prove the value of the land before the veterans' loan people down there, the land commissioner, would even accept the application.
Well, that put the monkey on the county judge's back and the county comptroller or the county treasurer, whatever they got.
And one other person, I forget.
Somebody that was supposed to be of integrity in the county.
And I eliminated that.
that possibility of fraud or conspiracy to defraud the government or the commission.
And then the next thing you know, he realized that they were out of money and they only had made, let's say, 10,000 loans.
And here's a million.
ex-servicemen wanting them.
So he sponsored a constitutional amendment of changing the law to where they would allocate or authorize another $200 million investment in it.
I passed 73.
That rocked along and it was so successful they passed a second amendment, increasing it again to maybe another $200,000, $300,000.
It was so successful of helping a man buy a piece of land.
And that set him up to where he was heir apparent and theoretically set up to run for the governorship.
And I used to visit with him.
I was his devotee during those years.
And I'd go down there, or we'd go to summer camp together.
I'd be in Austin to the highway landings, and I'd go up and talk with him.
He'd come to Dallas, and he'd come out the house.
And we'd proper feet up on the cocktail table and have a drink and eat peanuts and talk about problems that he was having.
He talked to me about running for governor, and about that time, the presidency of A&M became vacant.
Did the general want to run for governor?
Was he that inclined?
Well, he was that inclined, yes.
On the other hand, he said, Graber, where am I going to get a million dollars?
And it cost a million dollars to run a statewide race.
And I said, well, Earl, I don't know.
But I'll give you more on my share.
All he could do was thank me.
But he says, I'm just dumbfounded.
I don't know where to start raising that kind of money without incurring some obligation.
And I'm not going to be obligated to anybody if I run for governor.
Anyway, about that time, the presidency for A&M opened up, and I forget why it opened up, but it did.
And he talked to me about that.
What did he say about that?
He asked me what I thought about it.
I remember these words, and he reminded me of this, probably the next to last time I ever saw him.
My words were that, Earl, you can do more good for the state of Texas as president of Texas A&M than you ever could as governor.
Because a governor has certain political obligations, and you are building men over at A&M to run our state.
And your impact on the student body over there will turn out

such high caliber men that go to every crossroad in this damn state where your efforts as governor down there, you jockeying political patronage and deals with the legislature and you know those sorry bastards.
You're dealing with the lobbyists here and you're dealing with everybody and you're in the middle all the time.
How do you respond?
Well, he took the job as president of A&M.
Well, what did he think as far as your advice?
Of course, he said, I didn't know about that when I told him that he could make more impact on the state of Texas as president of A&M than he ever could think about as governor.
I don't know.
You didn't know him, but he kind of snickered and said, I don't know about that.
But he reminded me that I told him that.
Oh, the last two or three times I saw him, one of those two, the last two or three, he died very suddenly, and that was that.
But he was the salt of the earth.
There was no bad, and it was all good in him.
Because I knew him, and I knew him as a soldier.
I knew him in combat in Europe.
Did you know him in combat?
Oh, gosh, yeah.
What rank was he when after the war?
I mean as soon as the war was over?
Well he was lieutenant colonel and then he made colonel.
About the same time you did?
Yeah about the same time I did.
He was he was lieutenant colonel commanding his second range of battalion in Europe which is fighting a bunch of fighting SOBs.
They had that reputation and I'll show you his reputation.
They were, he personally was the first man up the cliffs in Omaha Beach.
And General Bradley wrote him up in his book, I don't know whether you've read it or not, of where he chastised Earl for going up there.
He was a commander.
He was supposed to see if the job was done, not go up there and do it himself.
And Earl told him that the only way he knew that the job was going to be done was to be up there and see if it was done.
And they went in and neutralized these shore defenses.
Some particular cannons they had up there, they had to neutralize to keep them firing on our people coming in, all that kind of thing.
I went to see him one time in Europe, and I was so mad at him I won't kill him.
He came in to the, we were in the Roar Valley, waiting for the American troops to capture the Roar Dam.
Otherwise, if we'd have started across there, they could open the dam up and wash us out.
Sure.
And we were up there for a week or more and
I forget the number of the division, but they gave some division this responsibility, and they tried at night, and they tried at daytime.
They couldn't do it.
The Germans just beat them back.
That's all they stood.
And somebody suggested about the Rangers.
Turned over to the Rangers, let them go do it.
And Earl was, his battalion was nominated to do it.
by the command of the Ranger Force.
And I don't know who that was.
I don't know who they were responsible to.
There was a special task force that was set up for specialized jobs, and I guess all the way back in the War Department in Washington.
But anyway, they gave that mission to the 2nd Ranger Battalion.
beefed him up, gave him a bunch of help, and he went in there and did it in one night, captured and intact.

And that left a bunch of the, our Corps, we were in the 19th Corps of the 9th Army, and that let our Corps go on across the valley, because they, with the Americans in control of the gates and all, they couldn't wash us out.
Well anyway, word circulated around through all our soldiers,
I had a fighting son of a bitch.
There was a fighting outfit.
And one of my six strippers, my operations sergeant, who was a hell of a fine man, came in to me three or four days later.
He says, Colonel, I want a bus, and I want to leave the outfit.
Of course, that floored me, because he was my right-hand operations sergeant.
What the hell are you talking about, sergeant?
You been drinking or something?
No, sir.
I want to join the 2nd Ranger Battalion.
Why do you want to do that?
Because they're fighting some bitches, and they got a colonel down there that's out in front of them.
And I want to go down there and fight with them.
Well, a man tell you that, you can't say, no, I won't approve your transfer.
And Earl wouldn't take him as anything but a private, because he didn't want to upset his esprit among his own people.
So this boy took a bus from Sixth Stryper
to one striper to join the 2nd Ranger Battalion.
Because of his admiration for Colonel Rutter.
And of course, I was only looking for Earl Rutter.
I'd known him in school and I'd known him since then.
What the hell is he doing proselyting my people like that?
But, uh... What did he say?
Oh, he just laughed at me and said, oh, get off my back.
Come on, let's have a cup of coffee and a donut.
I got some hot donuts down here.
And he said, that man came to me, and I guess it's true, that man came to me and wanted to join my battalion.
And I told him, hell, I couldn't take 6th Striper.
He said, well, I'll take the bus if you'll take me.
And when my operations sergeant told him that, he said, well, you go get transferred then.
I'll prove it when you come over here.
And I mean, what can you do with a man that you depend on and has that capabilities to the Army?
And he thought so well of Colonel Rutter that he would take a bus from Six Stripe to One Stripe to get to serve under you.
That's incredible.
That's right.
But that's Earl Rutter.
Let's talk about the changes.
That, to me, is the salt of the earth.
Yeah.
I never had anybody come and tell me they'd take a bus to come in my outfit.
But that old boy did.
Let's talk about the changes during the Rudder presidency, because they were fundamental changes, revolutionary changes to Texas A&M.
First, we allowed women, and then we allowed blacks, and then
all at the same time pretty much, then the end of the Mandatory Corps, and eventually this institution grows from 6,000 in 1960 to 34,000 today in 1981.
I mean, these are incredible changes.
That's right.
I like your opinion of these.
Well, all for the better.
Everything was for the better.
Now, let me tell you my story about Earl Rudder again as president of A&M.
He went down there.
Tom Harrington was still president, and he had the dual jobs.
And academically, Tom was probably qualified, but administrative-wise, he was not.
He taught me fish chemistry.
And so he was probably two, three years older than I am.
He was working on a doctor's degree or something and teaching, you know.
And he stayed with them and made them a good hand.
And he got up to be eventually president and then chancellor of the university, or his university by then.
No, it wasn't either.
It was still college.
Because Earl supervised that change in the name
University, or college?
College University.
He and I, in our living room over where you were last night, talked about that very thing before it ever, when he was proposing it, in his own mind, building this direction.
And what motivated him to thinking in those terms, he told me that when he went down there, A&M was getting about $500,000 worth of national grants a year.
from big corporations, you know.
It set up teacher chairs and research chairs, research laboratories and all this kind of thing.
And United Fruit Company was getting ready to set up a tropical fruit disease laboratory in Nevada School.
Yeah.
He said, Grandma, I've been up there three times now, and they won't even talk to me.
They just tell me they're not going to give any money to that college.
They give their money to universities.
And he said, I'll try to get in the back door.
I'll try to get in both side doors, and they won't even open the front door for me.
Talk to them.
And I said, well, hell, just change your name from college to university.
That's easy.
All you got to do is write an order.
And he said, oh, that's not that simple.
And then we talked about this thing.
He may have thought about it, but I ventured the approach to it.
And, well, what's going to happen?
I think it took a legislature move.
I said, well, I don't know about the legislature.
The first people you've got to sell are the damn ex-students, because there's no more vociferous crowd in the world than A&M ex-students.
And if you sell them on the program, why, it'll be easy.
If you don't sell them on the program, they'll crucify you.
And he said, well, that's the damn sure truth.
And so he set about a sales campaign, if that's a good way to put it, to the ex-students.
And pointing out the fact that he can't get an increase in the national corporation grants under the name of a college.
And he needs that money.
The college needs that money.
And the students received it affirmatively.
Then he went about it down to the legislature.
He still had to sell the board of directors on it.
Then the legislature got the thing changed.
And that to me was a turning point of his direction of making, turning A&M from
a country college to a great university.
That was the first step.
Sometime in the latter years of his life, he told me, you know how much grant we got last year?
Something over $15 million from $500,000.
Nothing in the world but changing the name from college to university.
Pretty new station here.
So he had a very far-reaching vision of making that a great university.
We talked about the enrollment.
We got 6,000 students down there when he went over there, and now they got 36,000 or something.
And he said, you remember when you went down there?
Yeah.
There weren't any girls around.
No, there sure weren't.
The only girls I ever saw were those laundry queens down there on the track Saturday night.
And he says, you know how many students the university's got?
No.
But he quoted it in the 15s of 20,000 or something like that.
University of Texas.
University of Texas.
And he says, the only reason is because they've got girls over there.
I said, well, hell, that's easy.
Just accept girls.
Well, we don't have the dormitories.
All the dormitories got urinals in them instead of commodes.
And just thinking loud of all the problems you've got to contend with.
And ultimately, would it be worth it?
And I assured him it would be worth every bit of it.
I know some of my contemporaries have kids that went to university because their girlfriend was going down to university.
Are their girlfriends going to SMU so they want to go to SMU?
They hate SMU with the guts, but their girlfriend's going out there, so that's where they're going to college.
And that's a change of philosophy among students today, that they want to be in a co-educational institution.
And so he said about the
getting the board of directors to accept girls.
And when they did, their student body started increasing on their straight up path.
Eight, 10,000 the second or third year to 12, 15,000 dollars, I mean 15,000 people to 20,000, 25,000 and so on.
Nothing in the world has accomplished that but co-educational education down there.
And Earl Rudder was the papa of that.
I discussed it with him.
Whether I planned to see it or whether he had it in his mind, I don't know and don't care.
But I know I did have a lot of discussion with him on it before it ever happened.
I said once in this interview, sometimes he used me as a trial balloon with ideas.
And he knew that I would tell him
I got that's right or hell no, Earl, I wouldn't touch you with a 10-foot pole.
And a lot of times he took, or it panned out that what I told him worked out, and sometimes he didn't accept it.
And that's certainly his privilege.
But Earl Rudder turned that college around to being a great university, set the stride for it to continue to be a great university,
His untimely death, I hope, didn't lose stride with it.
I know Dean Hubert, and I think he's a great teacher and educator, but I don't know what his administrator at Earl was.
I don't think he is.
He's a great educator, but there again, Tom
Herrington was a great educator, but he wasn't an administrator.
He couldn't go down to the legislation panel on the table and say, I've got to have $10 million or $20 million, $100 million, and get it.
And Earl did.
Now, what about those two other very important changes, one allowing blacks at A&M and the other ending the mandatory Corps of Cadets?
Would you address yourself to those?
Well, having blacks there is just as inevitable
getting up in the morning and washing your face and hands.
So much of the funds come from federal government.
I don't know how much.
If one dime comes from federal government, they get to tell you how to operate.
And that's by Supreme Court edict.
That's the law of the land, and you've got to like it.
I don't have any idea how many blacks have gotten down there,
I know there's not near as many racial-wise whites at Prairie View as there are blacks at A&M.
And I've been to Prairie View where they're taking reviews down there with him.
I took their final review one time down there.
It was a thrill of my life.
They've got an outstanding Corps.
And they're making lots of good army officers for the Army.
But anybody that fights that battle is just completely off base and not even in the ballpark, as far as I'm concerned, because first, that's the law of the land.
And second, it's morally right that you give those people the same advantage as I had.
And what they do is their business.
And 99% of them, I guess, frittered away.
But that 1% will pay off someday.
I know they will.
Now what about ending the Corps?
Well, I grew up in a different time.
I think that gets back to my philosophy on mandatory service to our country.
I think that everybody ought to be in the Corps.
Now whether that has enhanced or increased the enrollment or not,

Certainly they couldn't have a core down there, and I have no idea how many male or female students they have, but I guess 8,000 of that 30,000 are female, and that leaves 30,000 male, and you couldn't have a core of 30,000 people.
Financially and physically impossible.
Have they completely eliminated the core?
I thought they had the core.
No.
Volunteer, totally volunteer.
Yeah, greatly reduced.
Every year with the fish coming in, they ask people if they want to join the Corps or not.
And some do, and most of them don't.
They have about, I think it's 2,000 in the Corps out of 34,000.
Yeah.
Well, of course, I went down there.
Of course, they have female in the Corps.
Yeah.
I went down there, and there are different,
age where I just couldn't wait to get down there and be in the Corps.
That was in my goals of life from the time I was thinking about going to high school and all through my high school of junior ROTC.
I could pretty much have written
history of my life of getting into the Corps.
And at that time you either, if you went to A&M, you got in the Corps.
Physical rejects were, still wore the uniform, but they were, they were called something
So are you positive toward that move, then, to end the mandatory core?
How do you feel about it?
I know this must have been tougher, General Rutter.
This must have really been tougher, General Rutter.
I'm sure it was.
But he could see that what he was doing was right, but versus the fact that it built the student body from 6,000 to 36,000.
And you can't argue with that success.
So maybe the Mandatory Corps is not the answer.
To me, every youngster, male or female, that comes of age of 18 or 19 or something, bang, ought to go into service for two years or some adjustable time.
I don't care what it is.
But they ought to prepare themselves for the defense of our country.
And we got to talking about that thing.
Is someplace for women to serve their country just as well as
the big place in combat for men.

I think that every student, every youngster is obligated to pay their, if there's another way to put it, to pay their liability, their debt to our society of a year or two service to qualify them for that
privilege of defending our country.
I owed it to my country to serve.
I have never asked for or received one dime of compensation for having served my country.
And I don't ask it.
I have never conceived of asking it.
My country had been good to me.
It gave me an opportunity of an education to serve it and now to make a good living out of it.
And that's what life's all about.
On the other hand, I think everybody has that obligation.
And I strongly favor university military service at some age, whether it's 17 to 19 or 18
20 or what it is.
Across the board, every man, if he can't do active combat work, he can do the KP work, or he can do the typewriter picking, or he can do the administrative work, or he can do something.
But without exception, he should pay his, if it's a good way to put it, his interest.
toward the indebtedness of protecting this country.
But of course, he's born with a, by virtue of being an American citizen born here, he's got the finest place in the world to live.
And I humorously said to two, three people, they asked me about what is the finest thing I saw on our trip around the world.
The finest thing I saw was DFW when we hit there.
Bar none.
There's just no place like it.
And I've seen a lot of the world now.
So in other words, with every single one of these major changes toward Texas A&M,
You agree with those changes, and you think that they've improved this college to be a great university?
It's changed A&M from being a good college to a great university.
No question about it.
And it was the finest place to get an engineering degree or an agriculture degree when I went there.
But it's a better place today because of Earl Rudder.
No question about it.
Now we've covered your early years, your education, what it was like going to Texas A&M during the Depression, and your military career and your reserve career.
I think we've covered, I'm out of questions.
Do you have anything else that you thought was fundamental in your life or your career which you think we should cover?
Is there something I've missed?
No.
You're the expert here.
I'm not the expert.
I just thank God for my privilege of having been able to attend A&M.
And I know it made a better man out of me.
It equipped me to do the things I've done in the Army and in my civilian pursuits.
No question about it.
Had I not gone there, I'd never have accomplished it.
I'm looking forward to our 50th reunion next year.
Sometime in May of 1952.
Good Lord willing, the creeks don't get too high.
No, I have no inhibitions about singing.
A&M made a band out of me.
It equipped me to do the things I did.
It gave me the confidence that I could do whatever I wanted to.
Sometimes my sights haven't been at the tops, but I could have raised them.
Maybe I was complacent in having them set so high.
I don't know.
But I'm a dedicated A&Mx student.
Yeah, I can see that.
It's a great university.
It was a good school when I was there, but it's a great university.
Thanks a lot for this interview, General.
I really appreciate your time.
Well, the pleasure's mine.
